Development of an AR/VR-Based Virtual Robotics Laboratory for Experiential Learning
1. Introduction

Industrial robotics has become a fundamental component of modern manufacturing and automation. Industries such as automotive, electronics, logistics, pharmaceuticals, and heavy engineering rely heavily on robotic systems for precision, efficiency, and productivity. Robots perform complex tasks such as assembly, welding, packaging, inspection, and material handling.

However, despite the increasing importance of robotics in industry, most educational institutions lack access to advanced robotics laboratories. Industrial robotic systems are expensive, require specialized infrastructure, and involve safety risks when operated by inexperienced users.

As a result, robotics education in many universities remains largely theoretical, limiting students’ ability to develop practical skills.

To address this challenge, this project proposes the development of an AR/VR-based Virtual Robotics Laboratory, enabling students to interact with simulated industrial robots in an immersive digital environment.

This system will replicate real industrial robotics workcells, allowing students to:

Program robots

Visualize robot motion

Understand kinematics and coordinate systems

Simulate industrial tasks

Interact with robotic tools and sensors

The platform will provide hands-on experience without requiring expensive hardware, making robotics education more accessible, scalable, and safe.

2. Problem Statement

Industrial robots are widely used in modern manufacturing environments, but many educational institutions cannot afford to install advanced robotics laboratories due to high setup costs, infrastructure requirements, and safety constraints.

Robotics laboratories typically require:

Industrial robotic arms

Programmable logic controllers (PLCs)

Safety cages

Sensors and actuators

Industrial controllers

Dedicated lab space

The cost of setting up a robotics lab can range from ₹50 lakhs to ₹5 crores, depending on the equipment.

Because of these limitations:

Students often learn robotics concepts only through theory.

Practical experimentation opportunities are limited.

Access to industrial robots is restricted.

Many students graduate without practical robotics experience.

Additionally, industrial robotics systems require strict safety protocols. Allowing inexperienced students to operate real robots can pose safety risks such as:

Mechanical accidents

Electrical hazards

System damage

These challenges create a gap between academic learning and industry requirements.

Therefore, there is a need for a cost-effective, scalable, and safe learning platform that allows students to gain hands-on robotics experience.

An AR/VR-based virtual robotics laboratory can address these challenges by providing immersive simulations of industrial robotics systems where students can safely explore robotic programming and operations.

